y 4, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Nintendo Life review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2010/06/mischief_makers_retro |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |title=Mischief Makers (Nintendo 64) Review |last1=O'Neill |first1=Jamie |date=June 12, 2010 |work=Nintendo Life |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6POOZpyPp?url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2010/06/mischief_makers_retro |archivedate=May 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NP review\">{{cite journal |work=[[Nintendo Power]] |issue=101 |date=October 1997 |page=95 |title=Now Playing |url=https://archive.org/stream/Nintendo_Power_Issue_101_October_1997#page/n104/mode/1up }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NWR>{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/editorial/37358/virtual-console-could-help-wiisuscitate-u |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=Virtual Console Could Help Wiisuscitate U |last1=Brown |first1=Andrew |date=May 7, 2014 |work=Nintendo World Report |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PSuS871B?url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/editorial/37358/virtual-console-could-help-wiisuscitate-u |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NWR review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/23860/retro-revival-3-mischief-makers |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=Retro Revival #3: Mischief Makers |last1=Miller |first1=Zachary |date=August 13, 2010 |work=Nintendo World Report |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PSyhHMLR?url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/23860/retro-revival-3-mischief-makers |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 4\">{{cite journal |work=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=4 |date=May 27, 2004 |title=Nintendo's Greatest Games |page=24 |last=Davies |first=Jonti }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 31\">{{cite journal |work=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=31 |date=November 9, 2006 |title=Essential Nintendo 64 Games |pages=23, 26 |last=Allen |first=Mat }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 52\">{{cite journal |work=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=52 |date=June 19, 2008 |title=Full of Eastern Promise |page=36 |last=Bevan |first=Mike }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=UGO>{{cite web |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/marina-liteyears-mischief-makers |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=11 Strong Gaming Girls We Never Saw Again |date=June 30, 2010 |work=[[UGO Networks]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PSuiRvRG?url=http://www.ugo.com/games/marina-liteyears-mischief-makers |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n=== Additional sources ===\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n\n* {{cite journal |work=[[Nintendo Power]] |issue=101 |date=October 1997 |pages=18\u201327 |title=Mischief Makers |url=https://archive.org/stream/Nintendo_Power_Issue_101_October_1997#page/n19/mode/2up }}<!-- Gameguide spread of first three levels -->\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Treasure video games}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games|border=yes}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:1997 video games]]\n[[Category:Enix games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 64 games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 64-only games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling platform games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Treasure (company) games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games with 2.5D graphics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1997 platform game}}\n{{about|the video game|the art activist collective|The Mischief Makers|the TV series|Mischief Makers (TV series)}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Mischief Makers\n| image = Mischief Makers.jpg\n| alt = A female robot made of white, 3D spherical polygons is blasting towards the right side of the box art, with fist outstretched and a trail of fire behind her. On the ground is a legion of identical, sad-faced creatures. The logo is in big, green bubble letters, and the Nintendo 64 sidebar flanks on the right.\n| developer = [[Treasure (company)|Treasure]]\n| publisher = {{vgrelease|JP|Enix}}{{vgrelease|[[North America|NA]] / [[PAL region|PAL]]|[[Nintendo]]}}\n| director = Hideyuki Suganami{{r|MM credits}}\n| producer = Yuuchi Kikumoto{{r|MM credits}}\n| programmer = Masato Maegawa{{r|MM credits}}\n| writer = Hideyuki Suganami{{r|MM credits}}\n| composer = Norio Hanzawa{{r|MM credits}}\n| platforms = [[Nintendo 64]]\n| released = {{vgrelease|JP|June 27, 1997|NA|October 1, 1997|PAL|January 15, 1998}}\n| genre = [[Platformer]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Mischief Makers''''', released in Japan as {{nihongo|'''''Yuke-Yuke!! Trouble Makers'''''|\u3086\u3051\u3086\u3051!!\u30c8\u30e9\u30d6\u30eb\u30e1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc\u30ba|Yuke Yuke!! Toraburu M\u0113k\u0101su}} is a 1997 [[side-scrolling]] [[platform game|platform]] video game developed by [[Treasure (company)|Treasure]] and published by [[Enix]] and [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo 64]]. The player assumes the role of Marina, a robotic maid who journeys to rescue her creator from the emperor of Planet Clancer. The gameplay revolves around grabbing, shaking, and throwing objects. There are five worlds and 52 levels, and the game is displayed in [[2.5D]].\n\nThe game was the first 2D side-scrolling game for the Nintendo 64, and Treasure's first release for a Nintendo console. The company began ''Mischief Makers''{{'s}} development in mid-1995 with little knowledge of the console's features. The 12-person team wanted to make a novel gameplay mechanic, and implementing the resultant \"catching\" technique became their most difficult task. The game appeared at the 1997 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] and was released in Japan on June 27, 1997, and later in the United States, Europe, and Australia.\n\nThe game received \"mixed or average reviews\", according to video game review score aggregator [[Metacritic]]. Critics praised ''Mischief Makers''{{'s}} inventiveness, personality, and [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] fights, but criticized its brevity, low difficulty, low [[replay value]], sound, and harsh introductory learning curve. Retrospective reviewers disagreed with the originally poor reception, and multiple reviewers noted Marina's signature \"Shake, shake!\" [[sound bite]] as a highlight. Video game journalists cited ''Mischief Makers'' as ripe for reissue either through the [[Nintendo eShop]] or in a sequel or franchise reboot. In 2009, ''[[GamesRadar]]'' called it \"possibly the most underrated and widely ignored game on the N64\".\n\n== Gameplay ==\n\n[[File:MischiefMakers--article image.jpg|thumb|left|Marina grabs a bomb. \"Clanball\" platforms and warp stars float nearby.|alt=A rainbow-colored spectrum in a futuristic gauge is in the upper-left area of the heads-up display. Marina, the main character, has green hear and wears white. She stands on a platform made of bricks, each brick is inlaid with an identical sad-looking face of different proportions. Floating balls with the same face float on the screen, as do rotate, neon-colored stars.]] ''Mischief Makers'' is the first [[single-player]] 2D [[side-scrolling]] [[platform game]] on the [[Nintendo 64]] console.{{r|IGN review}} Its gameplay combines platform [[game mechanics]] with aspects from the action and puzzle genres.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} The characters and backgrounds are modeled in pre-rendered 3D{{r|NP review}} similar to ''[[Donkey Kong Country]]''{{'s}} \"Advanced Computer Modeling\".{{r|Nintendo Life review}} This style, with 3D backgrounds behind 2D gameplay, is known as \"[[2.5D|{{frac|2|1|2}}D]]\".{{r|IGN: Griffey}} Compared to previous Treasure [[Run and gun (video game)|run and gun games]], ''Mischief Makers''{{'s}} gameplay is more exploratory in nature.{{r|NWR review}}\n\nThe [[player-character]], a robotic maid named Marina, journeys to save her kidnapped creator.{{r|IGN review}} The story takes place on Planet Clancer, a world on the cusp of civil war due to the actions of its Emperor and his Imperial forces. The Emperor brainwashes Clancers to kidnap the visiting robotics genius Professor Theo.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} Theo's creation, the player-character Ultra-InterGalactic-Cybot G Marina Liteyears, pursues the professor and grabs, throws, and shakes the obstacles in her way, such as enemies, floating \"Clanball\" platforms, warp stars, and missiles.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} Almost all game objects can be grabbed, which lends towards the shake-based combat system.{{r|NWR review}} Marina can shake \"grabbed\" objects to throw them as projectiles or to find loot.{{r|Gamasutra}} Objects sometimes change functions when shaken, such as items that become homing missiles and guns with multi-directional shots.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} Some drop red, blue, and green gems, which restore player [[Health (gaming)|health]].{{r|AllGame review}} The health gauge in the corner of the screen shows the amount of damage Marina can take.{{r|manual p15}} The player can store up to two additional stock lives.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} Yellow gems hidden in each level extend the final cutscene's length.{{r|NWR review|Gamasutra|GS review}} Marina can run, jump, and boost (via jetpack) in the eight [[Cardinal direction|cardinal and ordinal directions]].{{r|NWR review}} She can also slide, hover, and roll.{{r|AllGame review}}\n\nThe game has five worlds with roughly twelve [[Level (video gaming)|levels]] apiece.{{efn|The five worlds are Planet Clancer, Migen's Shrine, Mt. Snow, Aster's Lair, and the Imperial HQ, and there are 52 levels accessed via a [[overworld|stage select]] screen.{{r|IGN review}}}} Some levels are action-only while others include puzzles. The player's goal is to reach a warp star at each level's end. En route, Marina shakes enemies, breaks blocks, uses weapons, and rides \"bikes\" and objects along wire path mazes.{{r|IGN review}} Each world has both final and mid-level [[Boss (video gaming)|bosses]]. The levels and boss fights use [[Scale (ratio)|scaling]] and screen rotation [[special effects]] to vary the gameplay.{{r|Nintendo Life review}}\n\nAlmost all things on Planet Clancer{{emdash}}including people, buildings, and pets{{emdash}}either wear or are inscribed with identical \"sad\" faces with red, glowing eyes.{{r|NWR review}} A Clancer named Teran substitutes for Marina in several brief areas and uses non-shake mechanics like punching, kicking, and [[double jump (video gaming)|double jumping]].{{r|NWR review}} A character named Calina, a petulant Clancer who imitates Marina, recurs throughout the game as a [[comedic device]].{{r|Nintendo Life review}}\n\n== Development ==\n[[File:N64-Console-Set.jpg|thumb|The Nintendo 64 console|alt=The Nintendo 64 controller is the light gray controller with three handles for the player's two hands. It has red, green, blue, and yellow buttons, an analog stick, and a directional pad. The controller is plugged into the charcoal gray Nintendo 64 with a light gray cartridge inserted. The sleek console is convex on its top and has two power switches and four controller ports.]] \n[[Treasure (company)|Treasure]] began to develop ''Mischief Makers'' in mid-1995. At the time, they knew little about the Nintendo 64's final technical specifications, graphics implementation, and [[development kit]], but were nevertheless interested in the console and it's improved \"[[pixel]] quality\".{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} Historically, Treasure developed games exclusively for Sega consoles,{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}}{{efn|Treasure continued to develop for the [[Sega Genesis]] even while Nintendo had market control because they found the Genesis development process easier.{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}}}} which made ''Mischief Makers'' their first release for a Nintendo console.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} Bringing ''Mischief Makers'' to the Nintendo 64 was a hardware-based decision:{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} the Nintendo 64's [[video game cartridge|cartridges]] were more expensive than [[CD-ROMs]], but they loaded data instantly and were thus more conducive for [[action games]] such as ''Mischief Makers''. However, Treasure [[CEO]] Masato Maegawa said that development for the Nintendo 64 had a harsher learning curve than even the [[Sega Saturn]]. Other than the special attention required to build a single boss in 3D, the team did not use features specific to the Nintendo 64 hardware.{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}}\n\nTreasure's founders had come from [[Konami]], where they worked on [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] games such as ''[[Castlevania (1986 video game)|Castlevania]]'' and ''[[Contra (video game)|Contra]]''.{{r|IGN review}} They found their development environment restrictive and left to try riskier concepts and to singularly focus on making \"great games\".{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} In the three years between Treasure's founding and ''Mischief Makers''{{'s}} development, the company released highly regarded games such as ''[[Gunstar Heroes]]''{{emdash}}known as \"one of the definitive [[16-bit era|16-bit]] action games\"{{emdash}}and ''[[Dynamite Headdy]]''.{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} An average of 12 people worked on ''Mischief Makers'', with up to 15 at times. Though the team was different in composition from that of previous Treasure titles, it included the lead programmer and character designer from ''Gunstar Heroes''. Treasure's CEO said that the company liked to expand into new genres, though they primarily work in genres where the staff had the experience. The company sought to depart from the ''Gunstar Heroes'' [[shoot 'em up]] design, and chose to build ''Mischief Makers'' around an original \"catching\" gameplay mechanic, which became the hardest aspect to implement.{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} While foreign (non-Japanese) aesthetics were popular with other Japanese developers, Treasure's CEO felt the company's games did not look \"particularly foreign\" and could appeal to Japanese audiences.{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}}\n\nThe game was Treasure's first to be published by [[Enix]]. The publisher sought out Treasure for their reputation in the action game genre, and had approached Treasure several times before the Nintendo 64 project surfaced.{{efn|Treasure CEO Maegawa was already fond of Enix, having applied to work there as a student (though he did not get the job).{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}}}} Upon choosing to make the game for the Nintendo 64, Treasure thought it would be a \"good idea\" to work with Enix.{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} And similar to how Treasure ended its historic loyalty to the [[Sega Genesis]] by developing ''Mischief Makers'' for Nintendo, Enix had just recently ended its historic loyalty to Nintendo by signing ''[[Dragon Quest VII]]'' of their ''[[Dragon Quest]]'' franchise to Sony. Neither Square or Enix built a \"special relationship\" with Nintendo specific for ''Mischief Makers''{{'s}} release,{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} though Nintendo later served as the game's publisher for Western markets.{{r|IGN: Nintendo to publish}} Prior to Nintendo proposing to publish the game in the West, Enix said it had no plans to release the game outside Japan.{{r|GPro107}} When their English localization of the Japanese game finished ahead of schedule, the North American release date was advanced two weeks accordingly.{{r|IGN: Griffey}}\n\n''Mischief Makers'' was the only game displayed at the Enix booth at the April 1997 Tokyo Game Show.{{r|EGM95}} It was later demonstrated at the 1997 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]]{{r|IGN: Nintendo to publish}} and released in Japan on June 27, 1997, the United States on October 1, and Europe and Australia on January 15, 1998.{{r|IGN review}} Its Japanese title is ''Yuke-Yuke Trouble Makers'', or ''Go-Go Trouble Makers''.{{r|IGN: Treasure talks}} Near the time of the game's Japanese launch, Treasure announced that they would continue to develop for the Nintendo 64 with the Japan-only ''[[Bakuretsu Muteki Bangaioh]]'', which was released in September and later introduced to North America as ''Bangai-O''.{{r|IGN: Bakuretsu}}\n\n== Reception ==\n\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 70/100{{r|Metacritic}}\n| Allgame = {{Rating|3.5|5|AllGame review}}\n| EGM = 8/10{{r|EGM review}}\n| Fam = 32/40{{r|Famitsu}}\n| GameFan = 95%{{r|GameFan review}}\n| GI = 7/10{{r|GI review}}\n| GSpot = 6.7/10{{r|GS review}}\n| IGN = 6.2/10{{r|IGN review}}\n| NGen = {{rating|3|5}}{{r|NG review}}\n| NLife = {{Rating|8|10|Nintendo Life review}}\n| NP = 6.9/10{{r|NP review}}\n}}\n\n''Mischief Makers'' received \"mixed or average reviews\", according to video game review score aggregator [[Metacritic]],{{r|Metacritic}} and a \"Gold Hall of Fame\" score of 32/40 from Japanese magazine ''[[Famitsu]]''.{{r|Famitsu}} Critics praised the game's inventiveness, personality, \"variety\", and boss fights,{{r|Nintendo Life review|AllGame review|GS review|EGM review}} and criticized its brevity, low difficulty, low [[replay value]],{{r|AllGame review|GS review|GI review}} sound,{{r|IGN review|NP review|GS review|NG review}} and harsh introductory learning curve.{{r|Nintendo Life review|AllGame review|EGM review}} Retrospective reviewers disagreed with the game's originally poor reception,{{r|Gamasutra|GamesRadar: untapped}} and multiple reviewers noted Marina's signature \"Shake, shake!\" [[sound bite]] as a highlight.{{r|NWR review|AllGame review|EGM review}} ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' awarded the game their silver award.{{r|EGM review}}\n\n''[[IGN]]''{{'}}s Matt Casamassina said that the game compensated for its average graphics with excellent level design and gameplay challenges. He added that the game's puzzles require thought, unlike those in other action/platform games, and that the game's objectives were not clear until after the first few levels. Casamassina praised the game's transparency effects, [[Spatial anti-aliasing|anti-aliasing]], [[mipmapping]], and scaling rotations.{{r|IGN review}} ''IGN'' described anticipation for the game as \"tremendous\",{{r|IGN: Nintendo to publish}} particularly among the game's market of \"younger gamers and 2D fans\".{{r|IGN: Griffey}} ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' thought that the game was the best side-scroller since ''[[Super Mario World]]''.{{r|NP review}} ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' wrote that \"only diehard 2D platform fans\" would be interested and did not feel that the game lived up to standards set by ''[[Super Mario 64|Mario 64]]''.{{r|NG review}} In contrast, ''[[GameFan]]'' said that ''Mischief Makers'' did for 2D what ''Mario 64'' did for 3D, and suggested that [[Sega]] should be influenced by the game.{{r|GameFan spread}} ''[[GamesRadar]]'' retrospectively called ''Mischief Makers'' \"pure, unadulterated awesome\" and \"2D brilliance\". The website summarized the game to be about \"grabbing sad-faced aliens, shaking them until gems come out, and then hurling them at other sad-faced aliens.\"{{r|GamesRadar: untapped}} Zachary Miller of ''Nintendo World Report'' asserted the game may be the console's most bizarre and surreal,{{r|NWR review}} but ''[[Gamasutra]]''{{'s}} John Harris said that the game's premise is \"only strange to people who have never heard of [[anime]]\".{{r|Gamasutra}} ''GameFan'' described the game as \"obviously deeply Japanese\",{{r|GameFan spread}} where \"old school gameplay and 64-bit visuals finally meet\".{{r|GameFan review}}\n\n[[Hirokazu Hamamura]] of ''Famitsu'' commended ''Mischief Makers''{{'s}} gameplay, which balanced its poor character design. Other ''Famitsu'' reviewers admired Treasure's signature robot designs and were puzzled by the company's choice to use buttons instead of the 3D [[analog stick]].{{r|Famitsu}} ''[[Nintendo Life]]''{{'s}} Jamie O'Neill praised the game's characters and disliked the controls. He compared the Calina character to the role of Shadow Mario in ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]''.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} O'Neill wrote that the intricate controls were \"the antithesis of a friendly, approachable, and intuitive platformer\" because the game used every button on the controller (including the [[directional pad]]), though he felt that players who persevered through the difficult controls would find them \"inventive and unique\".{{r|Nintendo Life review}} He added that the complex controls allowed for experimentation that led to new and fun gameplay, and though the throwing enemies mechanic seemed to follow from ''Gunstar Heroes'', the Clanball platforming was unintuitive.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} John Harris of ''Gamasutra'' wrote that the game borrowed other elements from ''Gunstar Heroes'', as the games were similar in protagonists, collectible gems,{{efn|He added that the gems awarded for \"A\" rating finish times were difficult to collect.{{r|Gamasutra}}}} and bosses.{{r|Gamasutra}}{{efn|Harris also put Marina's \"grab\" in a lineage of Treasure's signature [[counterattack]] mechanics (where a player can escape an attack with a well-timed button press), which he extrapolated out to counterattacks in ''[[Viewtiful Joe]]'' and ''[[Soul Calibur]]''.{{r|Gamasutra}}}} As the game took time to learn and understand, O'Neill left the reader to decide whether the game was \"ultimately convoluted or bordering on sophistication and genius\".{{r|Nintendo Life review}}\n\n''Nintendo Life''{{'s}} O'Neill thought the five world bosses were among Treasure's best (in particular, the transforming \"Cerberus Alpha\" boss), but found the mid-level bosses uninteresting.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} Peter Bartholow of ''[[GameSpot]]''{{r|GS review}} and ''Electronic Gaming Monthly''{{'s}} reviewers felt similarly. [[Sushi-X]] of ''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' added that the technique of looking for a boss's weak spot was similar to ''[[Metroid]]''.{{r|EGM review}} ''Famitsu'' reviewers praised how the game encouraged players to experiment with the basic \"grab, throw, and shake\" gameplay. They also appreciated the cadence of ''Mischief Makers''{{'s}} short levels.{{r|Famitsu}} O'Neill (''Nintendo Life'') thought the game had great variety in gameplay mechanics (from maze puzzles to outrunning lava), graphics (from bosses that scale back the screen to levels with screen rotation), and audio (from upbeat quirk to scary), and added that he was surprised to hear critics speak against the \"unique, varied, and dramatic\" sound.{{r|Nintendo Life review}} Scott McCall of ''[[AllGame]]'' too appreciated the sound, from the voice to the \"almost indescribable\" music.{{r|AllGame review}} ''Gamasutra''{{'s}} John Harris noted its \"tremendous variety\" in gameplay{{emdash}}from a ''[[Track & Field (video game)|Track & Field]]'' remake to outrunning a missile barrage{{emdash}}as rare for 2D platformers, and commented that \"it is obvious that Treasure poured their hearts into this game.\"{{r|Gamasutra}}\n\nPeter Bartholow of ''GameSpot'' summarized ''Mischief Makers'' as \"a good game that will leave players wanting more\".{{r|GS review}} He liked the bosses, which made the player use all available skills but felt they were short-lived and easily solved in the context of a short game with tutorials as one-fifth of its levels.{{r|GS review}} He did not consider the ending extension a suitable reward for returning to the levels, and predicted that most players would not finish the game more than once.{{r|GS review}} ''[[Game Informer]]'' echoed Bartholow's comments about the game's brevity, and named the game's seven-event Olympics as a highlight.{{r|GI review}} Sushi-X of ''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' wrote that the game felt incomplete and lamented that \"a decent player can finish the game in under three hours\",{{r|EGM review}} though ''Next Generation'' said the game was \"certainly long enough\".{{r|NG review}} The game's frequent reuse of a small selection of titles, objects, sound effects, soundtracks, and bland backgrounds (compared to the \"impressive\" boss battle animations and effects) led ''GameSpot''{{'s}} Bartholow to suggest that ''Mischief Makers'' was limited by its cartridge space. He concluded that the \"decent\" game would be \"truly excellent ... on another medium\".{{r|GS review}} Zachary Miller of ''Nintendo World Report'' reported that the graphics did not age well into 2010.{{r|NWR review}} ''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' wrote that the game is \"definitely a [[sleeper hit]]\".{{r|EGM review}} ''Hardcore Gamer''{{'s}} Ryan Cartmel said the game went \"largely unnoticed\",{{r|Hardcore Gamer}} while ''GamePro'' claimed that it had \"[developed] a strong following in Japan.\"{{r|GPro110}}\n\n=== Legacy ===\nVideo game journalists from outlets such as ''GamesRadar'' and ''Nintendo World Report'' cited ''Mischief Makers'' as ripe for reissue either through the [[Nintendo eShop]] or in a sequel or franchise reboot.{{r|GamesRadar: untapped|NWR}} ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' placed the \"masterpiece of mayhem\" 80th on their list of \"essential\" Nintendo 64 games for its \"unbridled quality\".{{r|Retro Gamer 31}} In 2009, ''GamesRadar'' called it \"possibly the most underrated and widely ignored game on the N64\".{{r|GamesRadar: untapped}}{{efn|In the years since, ''Retro Gamer'' reported ''Mischief Makers'' as a somewhat rare collectible, with a rarity score of 7/10.{{r|Retro Gamer 4}}}} The website wrote that ''Mischief Makers'' was received poorly because players wanted 3D instead of 2D gameplay from Nintendo 64 games.{{r|GamesRadar: untapped}} ''Gamasutra''{{'}}s John Harris added that those who gave it a \"bum rap\" missed a \"surprisingly clever\" game.{{r|Gamasutra}} [[UGO Networks|UGO]] remembered the game as innovative, though imperfect, and asked to see Marina reinterpreted and resurrected in a new game.{{r|UGO}}{{efn|Marina reappeared as an unlockable character in Treasure's 1999 ''[[Rakugaki Showtime]]''.{{r|Retro Gamer 52}}}}\n\n== Notes and references ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n=== References ===\n\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name