=\"GameFan review\">{{cite journal |work=[[GameFan]] |date=September 1997 |issue=57 |pages=26\u201327 |title=Viewpoint |author1=Glitch |author2=Knightmare |author3=E. Storm }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GameFan spread\">{{cite journal |work=[[GameFan]] |date=September 1997 |issue=57 |pages=76\u201381 |title=Mischief Makers |author=E. Storm }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=GPro107>{{cite magazine |first=Ken|last=Ogasawara|title=Yuke Yuke!! Troublemakers|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=107 |date=August 1997|page=36}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=GPro110>{{cite magazine |author=Four-Eyed Dragon |title=Mischief Makers |magazine=[[GamePro]] |issue=110 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |date=November 1997|page=103}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GamesRadar: untapped\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/123-games-with-untapped-franchise-potential/?page=2 |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=123 games with untapped franchise potential |date=April 30, 2009 |work=[[GamesRadar]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PStZaMCI?url=http://www.gamesradar.com/123-games-with-untapped-franchise-potential/?page=2 |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GI review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/nov97/mmaker.html |accessdate=May 9, 2014 |title=Mischief Makers |date=November 1997 |issue=55 |work=[[Game Informer]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980121112002/http://www.gameinformer.com/nov97/mmaker.html |archivedate=January 21, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GS review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/mischief-makers-review/1900-2544812/ |accessdate=May 9, 2014 |title=Mischief Makers Review |last1=Bartholow |first1=Peter |date=April 17, 1998 |work=[[GameSpot]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PJW8fgbQ?url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/mischief-makers-review/1900-2544812/ |archivedate=May 4, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hardcore Gamer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2013/09/19/graveyard-mischief-makers/56071/ |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=Graveyard: Mischief Makers |last1=Cartmel |first1=Ryan |date=September 19, 2013 |work=Hardcore Gamer |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PT9koLsO?url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2013/09/19/graveyard-mischief-makers/56071/ |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IGN: Bakuretsu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1999/06/24/unearthing-treasure-for-n64 |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |title=Unearthing Treasure for N64 |author=IGN Staff |date=June 23, 1999 |work=[[IGN]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PONPgDA0?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1999/06/24/unearthing-treasure-for-n64 |archivedate=May 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IGN: Griffey\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/08/06/griffey-mischief-makers-trade-spots |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |title=Griffey, Mischief Makers Trade Spots |author=IGN Staff |date=August 5, 1997 |work=[[IGN]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PNxfQAAc?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/08/06/griffey-mischief-makers-trade-spots |archivedate=May 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IGN: Nintendo to publish\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/06/11/nintendo-to-publish-mischief-makers |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |title=Nintendo to Publish Mischief Makers |author=IGN Staff |date=June 10, 1997 |work=[[IGN]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PNwwkNW2?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/06/11/nintendo-to-publish-mischief-makers |archivedate=May 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IGN review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/10/02/mischief-makers |title=Mischief Makers |last1=Casamassina |first1=Matt |date=October 1, 1997 |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=May 5, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PMFpJ8dX?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/10/02/mischief-makers |archivedate=May 6, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IGN: Treasure talks\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/04/15/treasure-talks-yuke-yuke |accessdate=May 5, 2014 |title=Treasure Talks Yuke Yuke |author=IGN Staff |work=[[IGN]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PMIz9x6o?url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1997/04/15/treasure-talks-yuke-yuke |archivedate=May 6, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"manual p15\">{{cite book |title=Mischief Makers Instruction Booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo of America]] |year=1997 |page=15 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Metacritic>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/n64/mischiefmakers |title=Mischief Makers (N64: 1997) |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=May 5, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304185036/http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/n64/mischiefmakers |archivedate=March 4, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MM credits\">{{cite video game |title=Mischief Makers |developer=[[Treasure (company)|Treasure]] |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |date=October 1, 1997 |scene=Credits }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NG review\">{{cite magazine|title=Finals|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=34|date=October 1997|page=169|url=http://www.next-generation.com/reviews/nintendo64/mischief.chtml |accessdate=May 9, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980204080243/http://www.next-generation.com/reviews/nintendo64/mischief.chtml |archivedate=February 4, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Nintendo Life review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2010/06/mischief_makers_retro |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |title=Mischief Makers (Nintendo 64) Review |last1=O'Neill |first1=Jamie |date=June 12, 2010 |work=Nintendo Life |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6POOZpyPp?url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2010/06/mischief_makers_retro |archivedate=May 7, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NP review\">{{cite journal |work=[[Nintendo Power]] |issue=101 |date=October 1997 |page=95 |title=Now Playing |url=https://archive.org/stream/Nintendo_Power_Issue_101_October_1997#page/n104/mode/1up }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NWR>{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/editorial/37358/virtual-console-could-help-wiisuscitate-u |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=Virtual Console Could Help Wiisuscitate U |last1=Brown |first1=Andrew |date=May 7, 2014 |work=Nintendo World Report |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PSuS871B?url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/editorial/37358/virtual-console-could-help-wiisuscitate-u |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NWR review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/23860/retro-revival-3-mischief-makers |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=Retro Revival #3: Mischief Makers |last1=Miller |first1=Zachary |date=August 13, 2010 |work=Nintendo World Report |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PSyhHMLR?url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/23860/retro-revival-3-mischief-makers |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 4\">{{cite journal |work=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=4 |date=May 27, 2004 |title=Nintendo's Greatest Games |page=24 |last=Davies |first=Jonti }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 31\">{{cite journal |work=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=31 |date=November 9, 2006 |title=Essential Nintendo 64 Games |pages=23, 26 |last=Allen |first=Mat }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Retro Gamer 52\">{{cite journal |work=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=52 |date=June 19, 2008 |title=Full of Eastern Promise |page=36 |last=Bevan |first=Mike }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=UGO>{{cite web |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/marina-liteyears-mischief-makers |accessdate=May 10, 2014 |title=11 Strong Gaming Girls We Never Saw Again |date=June 30, 2010 |work=[[UGO Networks]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PSuiRvRG?url=http://www.ugo.com/games/marina-liteyears-mischief-makers |archivedate=May 10, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n=== Additional sources ===\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n\n* {{cite journal |work=[[Nintendo Power]] |issue=101 |date=October 1997 |pages=18\u201327 |title=Mischief Makers |url=https://archive.org/stream/Nintendo_Power_Issue_101_October_1997#page/n19/mode/2up }}<!-- Gameguide spread of first three levels -->\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Treasure video games}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games|border=yes}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:1997 video games]]\n[[Category:Enix games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 64 games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 64-only games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling platform games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Treasure (company) games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games with 2.5D graphics]]\n", "name_user": "Martin IIIa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mischief_Makers"}
{"title_page": "Cameron Duke", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Cameron Duke|timestamp=20200418194413|year=2020|month=April|day=18|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Cameron Duke|date=18 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Cameron Duke\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| fullname             = \n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|2001|2|13}}\n| birth_place          = [[Overland Park]], [[Kansas]]\n| height               = \n| position             = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub          = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| clubnumber           = 28\n| youthyears1          = 2012-2020\n| youthclubs1          = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| years1               = 2019-Present\n| clubs1               = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| caps1                = 0\n| goals1               = 0\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national under-15 soccer team|United States U15]]\n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| nationalyears2 = \n| nationalteam2 = [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = \n| nationalgoals2 = \n| nationalteam3 = [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U18]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = April 18, 2020\n| ntupdate             = April 18, 2020\n}}\n\n'''Cameron Duke''' (born February 13, 2001) is an [[American]] [[association football|soccer player]] who currently plays for [[Sporting Kansas City]] in [[Major League Soccer]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cameron Duke |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/players/cameron-duke |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Youth Career===\nBorn and raised in [[Overland Park]], [[Kansas]], Duke comes from a big soccer family as his father, [[Chris Duke (soccer)|Chris Duke]], was an [[Indoor soccer| indoor soccer]] [[defender (association football)|defender]] for the [[Kansas City Comets (1979-91)|Kansas City Comets]], [[Kansas City Attack]], and [[Pittsburgh Stingers]]. His older brother, [[Christian Duke]], is currently the captain of [[Sporting Kansas City II]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cameron Duke |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/players/cameron-duke |website=MLS |publisher=MLS |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>.\nCameron Duke joined the [[Sporting Kansas City]] Academy in 2012, where he has featured for both the SKC Academy and the United States Youth National Team. Duke graduated from  [[Blue Valley West High School]] in May of 2019 and became [[Sporting Kansas City]]'s 11th ever homegrown player when he signed his first professional contract in July of 2019.\n\n===Professional===\nAs on of the nation's standout youth internationals, Duke signed his first professional contract with [[Sporting Kansas City]] in July 2019, becoming the 11th homegrown player in the organization's history. His contract keeps him with Sporting KC until 2022 with an option for 2023.\n\n===Honors===\n;Individual\n*Central Conference Best XI: 2018\n*Central Conference Player of the Year: 2018\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duke, Cameron}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sporting Kansas City players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Cameron Duke|timestamp=20200418194413|year=2020|month=April|day=18|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Cameron Duke|date=18 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Cameron Duke\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| fullname             = \n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|2001|2|13}}\n| birth_place          = [[Overland Park]], [[Kansas]]\n| height               = \n| position             = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub          = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| clubnumber           = 28\n| youthyears1          = 2012-2020\n| youthclubs1          = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| years1               = 2019-Present\n| clubs1               = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| caps1                = 0\n| goals1               = 0\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national under-15 soccer team|United States U15]]\n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| nationalyears2 = \n| nationalteam2 = [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = \n| nationalgoals2 = \n| nationalteam3 = [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U18]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = April 18, 2020\n| ntupdate             = April 18, 2020\n}}\n\n'''Cameron Duke''' (born February 13, 2001) is an [[American]] [[association football|soccer player]] who currently plays for [[Sporting Kansas City]] in [[Major League Soccer]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cameron Duke |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/players/cameron-duke |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Youth Career===\nBorn and raised in [[Overland Park]], [[Kansas]], Duke comes from a big soccer family as his father, [[Chris Duke (soccer)|Chris Duke]], was an [[indoor soccer defender]] [[defender (association football)|defender]] for the [[Kansas City Comets (1979-91)|Kansas City Comets]], [[Kansas City Attack]], and [[Pittsburgh Stingers]]. His older brother, [[Christian Duke]], is currently the captain of [[Sporting Kansas City II]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Cameron Duke |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/players/cameron-duke |website=MLS |publisher=MLS |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>.\nCameron Duke joined the [[Sporting Kansas City]] Academy in 2012, where he has featured for both the SKC Academy and the United States Youth National Team. Duke graduated from  [[Blue Valley West High School]] in May of 2019 and became [[Sporting Kansas City]]'s 11th ever homegrown player when he signed his first professional contract in July of 2019.\n\n===Professional===\nAs on of the nation's standout youth internationals, Duke signed his first professional contract with [[Sporting Kansas City]] in July 2019, becoming the 11th homegrown player in the organization's history. His contract keeps him with Sporting KC until 2022 with an option for 2023.\n\n===Honors===\n;Individual\n*Central Conference Best XI: 2018\n*Central Conference Player of the Year: 2018\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Duke, Cameron}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sporting Kansas City players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n", "name_user": "Wikipert22", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cameron_Duke"}
{"title_page": "Assia Wevill", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Assia Wevill\n| image       =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1927|05|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Berlin]], Germany\n| birth_name  = Assia Esther Gutmann\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=y|1969|03|23|1927|05|15}}\n| death_place = [[London]], England\n| death_cause = [[Suicide]]\n| nationality = German\n| other_names =\n| partner     = [[Ted Hughes]]\n| occupation  =\n| spouse      = Sgt. John Steele<br /> [[Richard Lipsey]]<br /> [[David Wevill]]\n| children    = 1\n| education   =\n| alma_mater  = [[University of British Columbia]], Vancouver\n}}\n\n'''Assia Esther Wevill''' (15 May 1927&nbsp;\u2013 23 March 1969) was a German woman who escaped the [[Nazism|Nazis]] at the beginning of [[World War II]] and emigrated to [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]], then later the United Kingdom, where she had a relationship with the English poet [[Ted Hughes]]. She killed herself and their four-year-old daughter Shura using a gas oven, similar to Hughes's first wife [[Sylvia Plath]]'s suicide, six years earlier.\n\n==Early life==\nAssia Gutmann was the daughter of a Jewish physician of Latvian origin, Lonya Gutmann, and a German [[Lutheran]] mother, Elisabeth \"Lisa\" (n\u00e9e Gaedeke).<ref>[https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/books/sorry-affair-1-723105]</ref> Her sister Celia was born on 22 September 1929 and she escaped the [[Nazism|Nazis]] at the beginning of [[World War II]] and emigrated to Israel.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} She spent most of her youth in [[Tel Aviv]]. Described by friends and family as a free-spirited young woman, she would go out to dance at the British soldiers' club, where she met Sergeant John Steele, who became her first husband and with whom she moved to [[London]] in 1946.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} According to her biographers, Yehuda Koren and Eilat Negev, \"she had entered an essentially loveless marriage with an Englishman at the age of 20 \u2013 largely to enable her family to emigrate to England.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=I'm going to seduce Ted Hughes|work=The Telegraph|author=Koren, Yehuda|author2=Negev, Eilat|last-author-amp=yes |date= September 9, 2006|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1528416/Im-going-to-seduce-Ted-Hughes.html}}</ref> The couple later emigrated to [[Vancouver]], Canada, where Assia enrolled at the [[University of British Columbia]] and met her second husband, Canadian economist [[Richard Lipsey]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lipsey|first1=Richard|title=Microeconomics, growth and political economy|date=1997|publisher=Elgar|page=xiv and footnote 4, page xxxv}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, on a ship to London, she met the 21-year-old poet [[David Wevill]]. They began an affair and Assia divorced Lipsey; she married Wevill in 1960.<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Haunted by the ghosts of love\n  | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n  | date = 10 April 1999\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/saturday_review/story/0,,307083,00.html\n  | location = London\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2007}}\n</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAssia was linguistically gifted. She had a successful career in advertising<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last=Koren|first=Yehuda|title=A Lover of Unreason|year=2006|publisher=Robson Books|location=London|isbn=1861059744|page=151}}</ref> and was an aspiring poet who published, under her maiden name Assia Gutmann, an English translation of the work of Israeli poet [[Yehuda Amichai]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Selected Poems |first=Yehuds |last=Amichai |authorlink=Yehuda Amichai |translator=Assia Gutmann |location=London |publisher=Cape Goliard Press |year=1968}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Selected Poems |first=Yehuds |last=Amichai |authorlink=Yehuda Amichai |translator=Assia Gutmann and Harold Schimmel, with collaboration of [[Ted Hughes]] |location=Harmondsworth |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=1971}}</ref>\n\n==Ted Hughes==\nIn 1961, poets [[Ted Hughes]] and [[Sylvia Plath]] rented their flat in Chalcot Square, [[Primrose Hill]], London, to Assia and David Wevill, and took up residence at [[North Tawton]], [[Devon]]. Hughes was immediately struck with Assia, as she was with him. He later wrote:\n\n:''We didn't find her - she found us.''\n:''She sniffed us out...''\n:''She sat there...''\n:''Slightly filthy with erotic mystery...''\n:''I saw the dreamer in her''\n:''Had fallen in love with me and she did not know it.''\n:''That moment the dreamer in me''\n:''Fell in love with her, and I knew it.''<ref>{{cite news|author=Hughes, Ted|title=Dreamers|work=Birthday Letters|publisher= Faber & Faber|date= 1998}}</ref>\n\nPlath noted their chemistry. Soon afterward, Ted and Assia began an affair. At the time of Plath's suicide, Assia was pregnant with Hughes's child, but she had an abortion soon after Plath's death. The actual relationship, who instigated it, and its circumstances, have been hotly debated for many years.<ref name=\"Sigmund-1999\">{{cite news\n  | title = 'I realised Sylvia knew about Assia's pregnancy&nbsp;- it might have offered a further explanation of her suicide'\n  | first = Elizabeth\n  | last = Sigmund\n  | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,3857472,00.html\n  | date = 23 April 1999\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nAfter Plath's suicide, Hughes moved Assia into [[Court Green]] (the Devon home at [[North Tawton]] he had bought with Plath), where Assia helped care for Hughes's and Plath's two children, [[Frieda Hughes|Frieda]] and [[Nicholas Hughes|Nicholas]]. Assia was reportedly haunted by Plath's memory; she even began using things that had once belonged to Plath.<ref>{{cite web\n  | first = Tim\n  | last = Morris\n  | title = The People in Sylvia's Life\n  | publisher = University of Texas, Arlington\n  | url = http://www.uta.edu/english/tim/poetry/sp/the%20people%20in%20sylvia.htm\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref> In their biography of Wevill, ''Lover of Unreason'', Koren and Negev maintain that she used Plath's items not from obsession, but for the sake of practicality since she was maintaining a household for Hughes and his children. On 3 March 1965, at age 37, Wevill gave birth to Alexandra Tatiana Elise, nicknamed Shura, while still married to David Wevill.\n\nOstracized by her lover's friends and family,<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Written out of history\n  | first1 = Yehuda\n  | last1 = Koren\n  | first2 = Eilat\n  | last2 = Negev\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/oct/19/biography.tedhughes\n  | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n  | date = 19 October 2006\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Sigmund-1999\"/> and eclipsed by the figure of Plath in public life, Assia became anxious and suspicious of Hughes's infidelity, which was real enough. Hughes began affairs with Brenda Hedden, a married acquaintance who frequented their home, and Carol Orchard, a nurse 20 years his junior, whom he would later marry in 1970. Assia's relationship with Hughes was also fraught with other complexities, as shown by a collection of his letters to her acquired by [[Emory University]].<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Ted Hughes Letters Go to Emory University\n  | first = Julie\n  | last = Bosman\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/10/books/10hughes.html\n  | date = 10 January 2007\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref> She was continually distraught by his reluctance to marry her and establish a home together, as well as his treatment of her as a \"housekeeper\".<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Ted Hughes, the domestic tyrant\n  | first = David\n  | last = Smith\n  | newspaper = [[The Observer]]\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/10/books.shopping\n  | date = 10 September 2006\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref> While he never publicly claimed Shura as his daughter, his sister Olwyn said that she believed the child was his.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GVMiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26|title=The Cambridge Companion to Ted Hughes|first=Terry|last=Gifford|date=30 June 2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|accessdate=30 May 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9781107493568}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n\nOn 23 March 1969, Assia killed herself and four-year-old Shura in their London home at 3 Okeover Manor, [[Clapham Common (ward)|Clapham Common]]. She had first sealed the kitchen door and window, then dissolved sleeping pills in a glass of water, chased with whisky, and then turned on the gas stove. She and Shura were found by the family's German au pair, Else Ludwig, lying together on a mattress in the kitchen.<ref name=NYTimes2009-03-23>\n{{cite news\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/24/books/24plath.html?em\n  | title = Son of Sylvia Plath commits suicide\n  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]\n  | first = Anahad\n  | last = O'Connor\n  | date = 23 March 2009\n  | accessdate = 23 March 2009\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140225204249/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/24/books/24plath.html?em| archivedate=February 25, 2014| url-status= live}}\n</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===In advertising===\nAssia composed the 90-second \"Lost Island\" advertisement for \"Sea Witches\" ladies' [[hair coloring|hair-dye]] product for both television and cinemas, called a \"breakthrough in type\" and a \"huge success\" by her biographers, Koren and Negev, that was \"applauded in theaters.\" The advert can be viewed in some classic ad compilations or sometimes as an online posting.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1080/01439685.2015.1129709|title = Cinema advertising and the Sea Witch 'Lost Island' film (1965)|journal = Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television|volume = 36|issue = 4|pages = 569\u2013586|year = 2016|last1 = Farmer|first1 = Richard|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\n===In literature===\n*Ted Hughes's volume of poetry ''[[Crow (poetry)|Crow]]'' (1970) was dedicated to the memory of Assia and Shura. \n*His poem \"Folktale\" deals with his relationship with Assia:\n\n:''She wanted the silent heraldry''\n:''Of the purple beach by the noble wall.''\n:''He wanted Cabala the ghetto demon''\n:''With its polythene bag full of ashes.''\n\n*Hughes published half a dozen poems he had written for Assia, which were hidden among the total of 240 in ''New Selected Poems'' (1989).\n*In \"The Error.\" he wrote:\n\n:''When her grave opened its ugly mouth''\n:''why didn't you just fly,''\n:''Why did you kneel down at the grave's edge''\n:''to be identified''\n:''accused and convicted?''\n\n*In \"The Descent\", he wrote:\n\n:''your own hands, stronger than your choked outcry,''\n:''Took your daughter from you. She was stripped from you,''\n:''The last raiment''\n:''Clinging round your neck, the sole remnant''\n:''Between you and the bed''\n:''In the underworld''\n\n*Assia appears as \"Helen\" in [[Fay Weldon]]'s novel ''Down Among the Women'' (1971).\n\n===In film and television===\n* In the feature film ''[[Sylvia (2003 film)|Sylvia]]'' (2003), Assia is portrayed by [[Amira Casar]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott |date=17 October 2003|title=FILM REVIEW; A Poet's Death, A Death's Poetry |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE2DF143EF934A25753C1A9659C8B63|accessdate=20 July 2018 |agency=The New York Times Company |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n* In October 2015, the [[BBC Two]] major documentary ''Ted Hughes: Stronger Than Death'' examined Hughes's life and work, and included an examination of the part played by Assia.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06j7pkl |title=BBC Two - Ted Hughes: Stronger Than Death |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=10 October 2015 |accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.elainefeinstein.com/TedHughes-Devon.shtml |work=Ted Hughes: The Life of a Poet|author= Feinstein, Elaine|author-link= Elaine Feinstein|title=Assia|pages=120\u2013124}} Extract from Chapter 8 - Devon\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zg9w Letters to Assia Wevill, 1955-1970]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wevill, Assia}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female suicides]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:German people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Filicides in England]]\n[[Category:People from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Socialites who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Suicides by carbon monoxide poisoning]]\n[[Category:Suicides in London]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Mandatory Palestine]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Ted Hughes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Assia Wevill\n| image       =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1927|05|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Berlin]], Germany\n| birth_name  = Assia Esther Gutmann\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=y|1969|03|23|1927|05|15}}\n| death_place = [[London]], England\n| death_cause = [[Suicide]]\n| nationality = German\n| other_names =\n| partner     = [[Ted Hughes]]\n| occupation  =\n| spouse      = Sgt. John Steele<br /> [[Richard Lipsey]]<br /> [[David Wevill]]\n| children    = 1\n| education   =\n| alma_mater  = [[University of British Columbia]], Vancouver\n}}\n\n'''Assia Esther Wevill''' (15 May 1927&nbsp;\u2013 23 March 1969) was a German woman who escaped the [[Nazism|Nazis]] at the beginning of [[World War II]] and emigrated to [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]], then later the United Kingdom, where she had a relationship with the English poet [[Ted Hughes]]. She killed herself and their four-year-old daughter Shura using a gas oven, similar to Hughes's first wife [[Sylvia Plath]]'s suicide, six years earlier.\n\n==Early life==\nAssia Gutmann was the daughter of a Jewish physician of Latvian origin, Lonya Gutmann, and a German [[Lutheran]] mother, Elisabeth \"Lisa\" (n\u00e9e Gaedeke).<ref>[https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/books/sorry-affair-1-723105]</ref> Her sister Celia was born on 22 September 1929 and she escaped the [[Nazism|Nazis]] at the beginning of [[World War II]] and emigrated to Israel.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} She spent most of her youth in [[Tel Aviv]]. Described by friends and family as a free-spirited young woman, she would go out to dance at the British soldiers' club, where she met Sergeant John Steele, who became her first husband and with whom she moved to [[London]] in 1946.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} According to her biographers, Yehuda Koren and Eilat Negev, \"she had entered an essentially loveless marriage with an Englishman at the age of 20 \u2013 largely to enable her family to emigrate to England.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=I'm going to seduce Ted Hughes|work=The Telegraph|author=Koren, Yehuda|author2=Negev, Eilat|last-author-amp=yes |date= September 9, 2006|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1528416/Im-going-to-seduce-Ted-Hughes.html}}</ref> The couple later emigrated to [[Vancouver]], Canada, where Assia enrolled at the [[University of British Columbia]] and met her second husband, Canadian economist [[Richard Lipsey]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lipsey|first1=Richard|title=Microeconomics, growth and political economy|date=1997|publisher=Elgar|page=xiv and footnote 4, page xxxv}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, on a ship to London, she met the 21-year-old poet [[David Wevill]]. They began an affair and Assia divorced Lipsey; she married Wevill in 1960.<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Haunted by the ghosts of love\n  | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n  | date = 10 April 1999\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/saturday_review/story/0,,307083,00.html\n  | location = London\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2007}}\n</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAssia was linguistically gifted. She had a successful career in advertising<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last=Koren|first=Yehuda|title=A Lover of Unreason|year=2006|publisher=Robson Books|location=London|isbn=1861059744|page=151}}</ref> and was an aspiring poet who published, under her maiden name Assia Gutmann, an English translation of the work of Israeli poet [[Yehuda Amichai]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Selected Poems |first=Yehuds |last=Amichai |authorlink=Yehuda Amichai |translator=Assia Gutmann |location=London |publisher=Cape Goliard Press |year=1968}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Selected Poems |first=Yehuds |last=Amichai |authorlink=Yehuda Amichai |translator=Assia Gutmann and Harold Schimmel, with collaboration of [[Ted Hughes]] |location=Harmondsworth |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=1971}}</ref>\n\n==Ted Hughes==\nIn 1961, poets [[Ted Hughes]] and [[Sylvia Plath]] rented their flat in Chalcot Square, [[Primrose Hill]], London, to Assia and David Wevill, and took up residence at [[North Tawton]], [[Devon]]. Hughes was immediately struck with Assia, as she was with him. He later wrote:\n\n:''We didn't find her - she found us.''\n:''She sniffed us out...''\n:''She sat there...''\n:''Slightly filthy with erotic mystery...''\n:''I saw the dreamer in her''\n:''Had fallen in love with me and she did not know it.''\n:''That moment the dreamer in me''\n:''Fell in love with her, and I knew it.''<ref>{{cite news|author=Hughes, Ted|title=Dreamers|work=Birthday Letters|publisher= Faber & Faber|date= 1998}}</ref>\n\nPlath noted their chemistry. Soon afterward, Ted and Assia began an affair. At the time of Plath's suicide, Assia was pregnant with Hughes's child, but she had an abortion soon after Plath's death. The actual relationship, who instigated it, and its circumstances, have been hotly debated for many years.<ref name=\"Sigmund-1999\">{{cite news\n  | title = 'I realised Sylvia knew about Assia's pregnancy&nbsp;- it might have offered a further explanation of her suicide'\n  | first = Elizabeth\n  | last = Sigmund\n  | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,3857472,00.html\n  | date = 23 April 1999\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nAfter Plath's suicide, Hughes moved Assia into [[Court Green]] (the Devon home at [[North Tawton]] he had bought with Plath), where Assia helped care for Hughes's and Plath's two children, [[Frieda Hughes|Frieda]] and [[Nicholas Hughes|Nicholas]]. Assia was reportedly haunted by Plath's memory; she even began using things that had once belonged to Plath.<ref>{{cite web\n  | first = Tim\n  | last = Morris\n  | title = The People in Sylvia's Life\n  | publisher = University of Texas, Arlington\n  | url = http://www.uta.edu/english/tim/poetry/sp/the%20people%20in%20sylvia.htm\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref> In their biography of Wevill, ''Lover of Unreason'', Koren and Negev maintain that she used Plath's items not from obsession, but for the sake of practicality since she was maintaining a household for Hughes and his children. On 3 March 1965, at age 37, Wevill gave birth to Alexandra Tatiana Elise, nicknamed Shura, while still married to David Wevill.\n\nOstracized by her lover's friends and family,<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Written out of history\n  | first1 = Yehuda\n  | last1 = Koren\n  | first2 = Eilat\n  | last2 = Negev\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/oct/19/biography.tedhughes\n  | newspaper = [[The Guardian]]\n  | date = 19 October 2006\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Sigmund-1999\"/> and eclipsed by the figure of Plath in public life, Assia became anxious and suspicious of Hughes's infidelity, which was real enough. Hughes began affairs with Brenda Hedden, a married acquaintance who frequented their home, and Carol Orchard, a nurse 20 years his junior, whom he would later marry in 1970. Assia's relationship with Hughes was also fraught with other complexities, as shown by a collection of his letters to her acquired by [[Emory University]].<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Ted Hughes Letters Go to Emory University\n  | first = Julie\n  | last = Bosman\n  | newspaper = The New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/10/books/10hughes.html\n  | date = 10 January 2007\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref> She was continually distraught by his reluctance to marry her and establish a home together, as well as his treatment of her as a \"housekeeper\".<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = Ted Hughes, the domestic tyrant\n  | first = David\n  | last = Smith\n  | newspaper = [[The Observer]]\n  | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/10/books.shopping\n  | date = 10 September 2006\n  | accessdate = 10 October 2010}}\n</ref> While he never publicly claimed Shura as his daughter, his sister Olwyn said that she believed the child was his.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GVMiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26|title=The Cambridge Companion to Ted Hughes|first=Terry|last=Gifford|date=30 June 2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|accessdate=30 May 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9781107493568}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n\nOn 23 March 1969, Assia killed herself and four-year-old Shura in their London home at 3 Okeover Manor, [[Clapham Common (ward)|Clapham Common]]. She had first sealed the kitchen door and window, then dissolved sleeping pills in a glass of water, chased with whisky, and then turned on the gas stove. She and Shura were found by the family's German au pair, Else Ludwig, lying together on a mattress in the kitchen.<ref name=NYTimes2009-03-23>\n{{cite news\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/24/books/24plath.html?em\n  | title = Son of Sylvia Plath commits suicide\n  | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]\n  | first = Anahad\n  | last = O'Connor\n  | date = 23 March 2009\n  | accessdate = 23 March 2009\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140225204249/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/24/books/24plath.html?em| archivedate=February 25, 2014| url-status= live}}\n</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===In advertising===\nAssia composed the 90-second \"Lost Island\" advertisement for \"Sea Witches\" ladies' [[hair coloring|hair-dye]] product for both television and cinemas, called a \"breakthrough in type\" and a \"huge success\" by her biographers, Koren and Negev, that was \"applauded in theaters.\" The advert can be viewed in some classic ad compilations or sometimes as an online posting.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1080/01439685.2015.1129709|title = Cinema advertising and the Sea Witch 'Lost Island' film (1965)|journal = Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television|volume = 36|issue = 4|pages = 569\u2013586|year = 2016|last1 = Farmer|first1 = Richard|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\n===In literature===\n*Ted Hughes's volume of poetry ''[[Crow (poetry)|Crow]]'' (1970) was dedicated to the memory of Assia and Shura. \n*His poem \"Folktale\" deals with his relationship with Assia:\n\n:''She wanted the silent heraldry''\n:''Of the purple beach by the noble wall.''\n:''He wanted Cabala the ghetto demon''\n:''With its polythene bag full of ashes.''\n\n*Hughes published half a dozen poems he had written for Assia, which were hidden among the total of 240 in ''New Selected Poems'' (1989).\n*In \"The Error.\" he wrote:\n\n:''When her grave opened its ugly mouth''\n:''why didn't you just fly,''\n:''Why did you kneel down at the grave's edge''\n:''to be identified''\n:''accused and convicted?''\n\n*In \"The Descent\", he wrote:\n\n:''your own hands, stronger than your choked outcry,''\n:''Took your daughter from you. She was stripped from you,''\n:''The last raiment''\n:''Clinging round your neck, the sole remnant''\n:''Between you and the bed''\n:''In the underworld''\n\n*Assia appears as \"Helen\" in [[Fay Weldon]]'s novel ''Down Among the Women'' (1971).\n\n===In film and television===\n* In the feature film ''[[Sylvia (2003 film)|Sylvia]]'' (2003), Assia is portrayed by [[Amira Casar]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott |date=17 October 2003|title=FILM REVIEW; A Poet's Death, A Death's Poetry |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE2DF143EF934A25753C1A9659C8B63|accessdate=20 July 2018 |agency=The New York Times Company |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n* In October 2015, the [[BBC Two]] major documentary ''Ted Hughes: Stronger Than Death'' examined Hughes's life and work, and included an examination of the part played by Assia.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06j7pkl |title=BBC Two - Ted Hughes: Stronger Than Death |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=10 October 2015 |accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.elainefeinstein.com/TedHughes-Devon.shtml |work=Ted Hughes: The Life of a Poet|author= Feinstein, Elaine|author-link= Elaine Feinstein|title=Assia|pages=120\u2013124}} Extract from Chapter 8 - Devon\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wevill, Assia}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:Female suicides]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:German people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Filicides in England]]\n[[Category:People from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Socialites who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Suicides by carbon monoxide poisoning]]\n[[Category:Suicides in London]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Mandatory Palestine]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Ted Hughes]]\n", "name_user": "A.C.Butner", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assia_Wevill"}
{"title_page": "John Dehlin", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John P. Dehlin\n| image              = JohnDehlin.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1969}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Press |first=Associated |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2947941/Mormon-runs-website-doubting-members-ousted.html |title=John Dehlin gets kicked out of the Mormon church after refusing to shut down his website Mormonstories.org &#124; Daily Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=February 10, 2015 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=(19 years ago) |url=http://voters.findthedata.com/l/78808477/John-Parkinson-Dehlin |title=John Parkinson Dehlin &#124; Utah Voter |publisher=Voters.findthedata.com |date= |accessdate=April 18, 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Boise, Idaho]], US\n| alma_mater         = [[Brigham Young University]] (BS)<br />[[Utah State University]] (MS, PhD)<ref name=\"johndehlin.com\">{{cite web|url=http://johndehlin.com/privatepractice/ |title=Private Practice \u2013 John Dehlin, Ph.D |publisher=Johndehlin.com |date= 2015-07-24|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| occupation         = [[New media]] [[journalist]] and [[Pundit|commentator]]<br />Scholar<br /> [[Moral entrepreneur]] <br />[[Faith crisis]] [[Coaching|coach]]<br />\n| spouse             = Margi Weber Dehlin<ref name=Tedxusu/>\n| children           = \n| website            = http://johndehlin.com/\n}}\n\n'''John Parkinson Dehlin'''<ref>{{cite web|author={{ authors[i].name }} |url=https://www.scribd.com/user/298878004/John-Parkinson-Dehlin |title=John Parkinson Dehlin (john1parkinson1dehli) 2 uploads |publisher=Scribd |date=September 28, 2015 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|'|l|\u026a|n}} is a podcast host and excommunicated member of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church). Dehlin founded the [[Mormon Stories Podcast]], as well as several other [[Mormon]]-themed [[podcast]]s, [[blog]]s, and web sites,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mormonstories.org |title=Mormon Stories Podcast  |publisher=openstoriesfoundation.org |date= |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> and was an influential early participant in the [[Mormon blogosphere]], and blogs at [[Patheos.com]]. He has advocated for the rights of [[Religious skepticism|skeptics]] in Mormonism, [[LGBT]] rights, equality for women, and other individual views outside mainstream Mormonism.<ref name=\"johndehlin.com\"/><ref name=Tedxusu>{{citation |contribution-url= http://www.ted.com/tedx/events/9015 |contribution= TEDxUSU: Survive |place= [[Utah State University]] |url= http://www.ted.com/tedx/events |title= TEDx Events  |publisher= [[TED.com]] |date= November 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Post by Joanna Brooks |url=http://www.religiondispatches.org/dispatches/joannabrooks/4859/landmark_survey_of_lgbtq_mormons_launched_/ |title=Landmark Survey of LGBTQ Mormons Launched |publisher=Religion Dispatches |date=July 13, 2011 |accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Youth and early career==\nBorn in [[Boise, Idaho]] and raised in [[Katy, Texas]],<ref name=MMprofile>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Author Profile: John Dehlin|work=Mormon Matters|url=http://mormonmatters.org/author/admin/|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828230534/http://mormonmatters.org/author/admin/|archive-date=August 28, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he attended [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) in [[Provo, Utah]].  He graduated [[summa cum laude]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] in 1993.<ref name=OCWCprofile>{{cite web|title=User Profile: John Dehlin |publisher=OpenCourseWare Consortium |url=http://ohana.mit.edu/ocwc/display/~jdehlin |accessdate=July 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908043216/http://ohana.mit.edu/ocwc/display/~jdehlin |archivedate=September 8, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Dehlin worked for five years in software and as a consultant for [[Bain & Company]], [[Arthur Andersen]], [[Citicorp]], Heidrick & Struggles, and the LDS Church. He then worked at [[Microsoft]] for seven years in programs for [[Software developer|developers]], [[marketing]], speech technologies, and [[Tech demo|product demos]].<ref name=OCWCprofile/> Dehlin's brother, [[Joel Dehlin]], also worked at Microsoft, and became the [[chief information officer]] of the LDS Church in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, Joel |title=About Joel |work=Joel Dehlin Weblog |url=http://www.ldscio.org/about-joel/ |accessdate=December 8, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517085205/http://www.ldscio.org/about-joel/ |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Dehlin moved to [[Logan, Utah]], to begin work under [[David A. Wiley]] at [[Utah State University]] (USU) on [[OpenCourseWare]]-related projects.<ref name=OCWCpost>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Meet and Greet|date=March 15, 2007|work=OpenCourseWare Consortium Forum|publisher=OpenCourseWare Consortium|url=http://www.ocwconsortium.org/ocwcforum/viewtopic.php?t=6&sid=a9d7085c396ee8d6167b01af7ae91ebf|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604003628/http://www.ocwconsortium.org/ocwcforum/viewtopic.php?t=6|archive-date=June 4, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  Dehlin would serve two years as USU's OpenCourseWare Consortium Coordinator and Director of Outreach for the Center for Open and Sustainable Learning, promoting OpenCourseWare to other universities,<ref name=OCWCprofile/> and a few years as director of the [[OpenCourseWare]] Consortium for the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]. In 2007, while at USU, Dehlin also completed a [[Master of Science]] degree in [[Instructional Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=I did it|work=Mormon Stories|date=December 16, 2007|url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=376|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> In January 2007, [[MIT]] hired Dehlin as the Director of the [[OpenCourseWare]] Consortium.<ref name=OCWCpost/> In 2015 Dehlin received his doctorate in clinical and counseling psychology at USU.<ref name=\"USU University Libraries\">{{Cite journal | url=http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/etd/4251/ | title=USU University Libraries | journal=All Graduate Theses and Dissertations | accessdate=August 22, 2015| date=May 2015 | last1=Dehlin | first1=John }}</ref>\n\n==New media==\n===Sunstone===\nDuring Dehlin's early career developing [[massive open online course]]s (MOOCs) he had branched into Latter-day Saint themed [[new media]]. Dehlin approached the [[Sunstone Education Foundation]] and presented to its Board of Directors about the importance of participating in developing internet communities through blogging and podcasting, in order to address the then limited internet presence for constructive Mormon intellectual sources. The Board accepted his offer to initiate these programs<ref name=MStar>{{cite web|author=Goble, Clark|title=M* Interviews\u2026 John Dehlin|work=The Millennial Star|date=September 26, 2005|url=http://www.millennialstar.org/2005/09/26/m-interviews-john-dehlin/|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131021185604/http://www.millennialstar.org/m-interviews-john-dehlin/|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> and, in September 2005, Dehlin joined the Board of Directors and began a Sunstone podcast as well as ''SunstoneBlog''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wotherspoon, Dan |title=Bloggin and Podcasting Sunstone Style! |date=September 15, 2005 |work=SunstoneBlog |publisher=Sunstone Education Foundation |url=http://sunstoneblog.com/2005/09/15/blogging-and-podcasting-sunstone-style/ |accessdate=July 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905111435/http://sunstoneblog.com/2005/09/15/blogging-and-podcasting-sunstone-style/ |archivedate=September 5, 2008 }}</ref>  In July 2007, he also became executive director of the Sunstone Education Foundation, in which he was to focus on strategic initiatives to strengthen Sunstone's position as an open forum for Mormon issues.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunstone foundation hires executive director|date=July 28, 2007|work=[[Deseret News]]|url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,695195330,00.html|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>  In that role, he increased organizational focus on its longstanding motto, \"faith seeking understanding\", and worked to attract new and younger membership.<ref>{{cite news|author=Moore, Carrie A.|title=New direction for Sunstone?|work=[[Deseret Morning News]]|date=August 7, 2007|location=Salt Lake City|url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,695198451,00.html?pg=1|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>  Dehlin resigned from Sunstone in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=<comment>|work=The New Mormon History|publisher=Latter-day Commentary|date=June 8, 2008|url=http://latterdaycommentary.blogspot.com/2008/05/new-mormon-history-grant-palmer.html#c474708688441700241|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Mormon Stories'' ===\n{{main|Mormon Stories Podcast}}\nIn September 2005, after experiencing doubts in his faith and subsequently finding reasons to remain a member of the LDS Church, Dehlin created the Mormon Stories podcast as an open discussion of Mormon issues, intending to give listeners reasons to remain in the church.<ref name=MS1>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Mormon Stories Podcast # 001: Bad Baptisms? My Mission Experience in Guatemala|work=Mormon Stories|date=September 4, 2005|url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=4|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> Through interviews, Mormon Stories focused on varying Mormon experiences and perspectives. <!--To date, listenership at times exceeds 25,000 downloads per episode.--> Mormon Stories has been featured in many venues, including being broadcast on [[KVNU]] in [[Logan, Utah]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Grover, Tom|title=John Dehlin, Mormon Stories featured in today's Herald Journal|date=January 3, 2008|publisher=KVNU\u2019s For The People|url=http://kvnuforthepeople.com/?p=1258|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIntermittently conflicted about continuing ''Mormon Stories'', Dehlin stopped and restarted the project a few times.<ref name=WhatIsWas>{{cite web | title=What is/was Mormon Stories? | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=April 14, 2009 |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:2i027H1AlakJ:mormonstories.org/%3Fp%3D478+site:mormonstories.org+%22creative+commons%22&cd=2&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us&client=firefox-a}} {{dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Some Bonus Material, and a Break | date=December 25, 2007 | work=Mormon Stories | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=383 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref>  In January 2010 Dehlin resumed the blog and podcast, focusing on faith crises and mental illness. The podcast has featured many notable guests,<ref>{{cite web | title=Mormon Stories 2010 \u2014 A New Direction | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=January 15, 2010 | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=716 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref> beginning with interviews of [[Joanna Brooks]] and [[John C. Hamer]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Mormon Stories # 112 & 113: Joanna Brooks Parts 1 and 2 | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=January 20, 2010 | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=738 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Mormon Stories # 116: John Hamer Pt. 1 \u2014 The LDS Succession Crisis of 1844 and the Beginnings of the RLDS Church | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=January 24, 2010 | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=792 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref> Two other regular hosts joined Dehlin in conducting interviews for the podcast: Dan Wotherspoon, former editor of ''[[Sunstone (magazine)|Sunstone]]'' magazine; and Natasha Helfer Parker, a licensed clinical marriage and family therapist.\n\n== Criticisms==\n===Sexism===\nDehlin has been criticized by Kate Kelly, founder of <i>Ordain Women</i>, and Kristy Money for having Money and other female podcast hosts work without pay. Kelly deemed such a practice \"unacceptable.\"<ref name=\"John Dehlin and the women problem\">{{Cite web| title=\"John Dehlin and the women problem\"|url=https://dearjohndehlin.wordpress.com/2017/05/25/john-dehlin-and-the-women-problem/}}</ref>\n==Sexual Harassment===\nAccording to Kelly, one of Dehlin's Open Stories foundation filed a sexual harassment complaint in her state against Dehlin.{{Cite web| title=\"John Dehlin and the women problem\"|url=https://dearjohndehlin.wordpress.com/2017/05/25/john-dehlin-and-the-women-problem/}}</ref>\n=== Other blogs ===\n\nIn June 2007, Dehlin started ''Mormon Matters'' as a blog and weekly podcast.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mormonmatters.org/mormon-matters-undergoing-re-design/ | title=About&#124;Mormon Matters | accessdate=May 22, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608115748/http://mormonmatters.org/mormon-matters-undergoing-re-design/ | archive-date=June 8, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>  The format was a discussion panel on events, culture, politics and spirituality within Mormonism.  Panelists were to represent different sides of each issue, although the show later struggled to retain regular conservative LDS panelists.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Desperately Seeking Conservative LDS Panelist(s)|work=Mormon Matters blog|date=July 14, 2007|url=http://mormonmatters.org/2007/07/14/desperately-seeking-lds-conservative-panelists/|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828221809/http://mormonmatters.org/2007/07/14/desperately-seeking-lds-conservative-panelists/|archive-date=August 28, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In early 2008, Dehlin converted ''Mormon Matters'' into a group blog and lessened emphasis on new podcast episodes,.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Looking to turn Mormon Matters into a Group Blog|work=Mormon Matters blog|date=January 9, 2008|url=http://mormonmatters.org/2008/01/09/looking-to-turn-mormon-matters-into-a-group-blog/|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726231246/http://mormonmatters.org/2008/01/09/looking-to-turn-mormon-matters-into-a-group-blog/|archive-date=July 26, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Dehlin resumed the ''Mormon Matters'' podcast on March 5, 2011 with Dan Wotherspoon as the host, and [[Joanna Brooks]] as a frequent co-host.\n\nDehlin is also the co-founder of the pro-LGBT ''Mormons for Marriage'' website.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.mormonsformarriage.com | title=Mormons for Marriage}}</ref> He  co-founded ''[[Stay LDS]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staylds.com |title=Stay LDS / Mormon &#124; New Ways to Stay Connected |publisher=Staylds.com |date= |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref> a community that was dedicated to helping unorthodox Mormons stay in the LDS Church.<ref>{{cite news | author=Dobner, Jennifer | title=Mormons in crisis find online refuge | work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]] | date=July 20, 2009 | url=http://www.sltrib.com/faith/ci_12871883 | accessdate=January 28, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604200157/http://www.sltrib.com/faith/ci_12871883 | archive-date=June 4, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDehlin briefly blogged at a non-partisan religion website [[Patheos.com]] in a current-issues/events dialogue format with [[Mormon studies]] scholar [[Patrick Q. Mason]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/4373196-155/lds-scholar-ex-mormon-team-up-on|title=LDS scholar, ex-Mormon team up on new blog to debate key topics facing the faith|first=Peggy Fletcher Stack The Salt Lake|last=Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==LDS Church membership==\nFrom 1988 to 1990, Dehlin served as an LDS Church [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary]] in Guatemala. According to Dehlin, his [[Mission (LDS Church)|mission]] began baptizing up to 700 converts per month using practices he believed to be deceptive. After reporting this to an  [[apostle (Latter Day Saints)|apostle]], [[Dallin H. Oaks]], Dehlin was transferred and finished his two-year missionary term in Tempe, Arizona. Dehlin remained an active, faithful member of the LDS Church for the next 20 years.<ref name=MS1/>\n\nIn the Spring of 2011, Dehlin stated he had become inactive in the LDS Church (i.e., not attending weekly services), citing an inability to believe some of the church's claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.newordermormon.org/viewtopic.php?t=20463 |title=New Order Mormon \u2022 View topic - Conversation on FB with a friend, because oh John Dehlin |publisher=Forum.newordermormon.org |date= |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postmormon.org/exp_e/index.php/discussions/viewthread/28352/ |title=Support for People as they Leave or Consider Leaving the Mormon or LDS Church &#124; The Community Forum &#124; Yes, John Dehlin has left the Church |publisher=PostMormon.org |date= |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, Dehlin was investigated by his local church leaders regarding his online activity, culminating in a request by Dehlin for greater privacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mormonstories.org/did-you-ask-to-be-excommunicated/ |title=Did you ask to be excommunicated? |publisher=Mormon Stories |date= 2014-06-27|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2014, Dehlin had faced church disciplinary hearings without any resulting disciplinary action.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|last1=Walch|first1=Tad|title=Mormon critic John Dehlin says he'll face church disciplinary council|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865619676/Mormon-critic-John-Dehlin-says-hell-face-church-disciplinary-council.html?pg=all|accessdate=May 28, 2015|newspaper=Deseret News|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref> In January 2015, Dehlin's [[stake president]] initiated another disciplinary council,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goodstein|first1=Laurie|title=John Dehlin, Mormon Critic, Facing Excommunication|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/16/us/john-dehlin-mormon-critic-facing-excommunication.html|accessdate=January 15, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.sltrib.com/home/2089207-155/disciplinary-council-delayed-for-mormon-stories|newspaper = Salt Lake Tribune|title = Disciplinary council delayed for 'Mormon Stories' podcaster John Dehlin|first = Kristen|last = Moulton|date = January 22, 2015}}</ref> which determined Dehlin's online activity constituted apostasy.  He was [[Excommunication#The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|excommunicated]] for \"conduct contrary to the laws and order of the church.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name = walch>{{cite web|url = http://www.ksl.com/?sid=33422568&nid=148&title=john-dehlin-excommunicated-from-lds-church|publisher = KSL|title = John Dehlin excommunicated from LDS Church|first = Tad |last = Walch|date =February 10, 2015}}</ref> Dehlin appealed to the [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] on March 10, 2015, stating his actions had not met the church's definition of apostasy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/2275172-155/mormon-critic-john-dehlin-appeals-lds| newspaper=Salt Lake Tribune|title=Mormon critic John Dehlin appeals LDS excommunication| first = Peggy|last=Fletcher Stack|date = March 10, 2015|authorlink=Peggy Fletcher Stack}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/03/11/mormon-critic-john-dehlin-appeals-lds-excommunication/ |title=Mormon critic John Dehlin appeals LDS excommunication &#124; Religion News Service |publisher=Religionnews.com |date=March 11, 2015 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.newsweek.com/mormon-church-jesus-christ-latter-day-saints-james-hamula-648468 | title=Will we ever know why the Mormons booted out a top official for the first time in decades?| date=2017-08-09}}</ref> In July and August 2015, the First Presidency notified Dehlin via his stake president of the denial of his appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hjnews.com/allaccess/dehlin-upset-over-church-handling-of-excommunication-appeal/article_8fbf45da-5106-5a18-bf02-c02eebf70cbf.html|title=Dehlin upset over church handling of excommunication appeal|first=Kevin Opsahl staff|last=writer}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://johndehlin.com/ Official site]\n* [http://mormonstories.org/ ''Mormon Stories''], Dehlin's most well-known blog and podcast\n* [http://mormonstories.org/?page_id=102 Dehlin's list of episodes for ''Mormon Stories'', ''Sunstone'', and ''Mormon Matters'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140715092531/http://mormonmatters.org/2009/08/20/5-questions-after-5-years-%E2%80%93-from-a-longtime-%E2%80%98nacle-wannabe/ \"5 Questions After 5 Years \u2013 From A Longtime 'Nacle Wannabe,\"] by John Dehlin\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100119005050/http://ldspsychology.com/ Ldspsychology.com], one of Dehlin's blogs, started in 2009\n*{{Cite journal|title = The Odd Couple: Story and Community: John Dehlin's Mormon Stories project has a contradiction at its center. Whether it's a fatal error or a brilliant accident is yet to be seen|first = Rosalynde|last = Welch|date = June 28, 2012|publisher = [[Patheos]]|url = http://www.patheos.com/Mormon/Odd-Couple-Rosalynde-Welch-06-29-2012.html}}\n\n;Multi-media\n* {{cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0MxCXjfAunk |title=The Ally Within|publisher=[[TEDx]] |type = video of address|date= November 5, 2013}}\n* {{cite news|url = http://www.sltrib.com/home/2085731-155/trib-talk-john-dehlin-on-mormon|title = John Dehlin on 'Mormon Stories,' apostasy|type = interview video|author = [[Jennifer Napier-Pearce]]|newspaper = [[Salt Lake Tribune]]|date = January 22, 2015}}\n* {{cite web|url = http://hwcdn.libsyn.com/p/3/e/8/3e89a0e4190d5d6d/MormonTransitions-001-JohnDehlinUVUKeynote.mp3?c_id=9970211&expiration=1448041239&hwt=9867a9cc3b04e62eb602aa316cea34c8 |title=An Evening with John Dehlin: \"What I've Learned from 15-plus Years of Mormon Transitioning\" |type = speech audio|author = Utah Valley Post-Mormons|publisher = hwcdn.libsyn.com|date =  August 18, 2015}}\n\n;WorldCat\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-no2007-140179}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!--Dummy edit for edit summary, delete me-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dehlin, John}}\n[[Category:20th-century Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:Former Latter Day Saints]]\n[[Category:American Mormon missionaries in Guatemala]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mormon studies]]\n[[Category:Mormon bloggers]]\n[[Category:OpenCourseWare]]\n[[Category:Utah State University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:People excommunicated by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John P. Dehlin\n| image              = JohnDehlin.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1969}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Press |first=Associated |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2947941/Mormon-runs-website-doubting-members-ousted.html |title=John Dehlin gets kicked out of the Mormon church after refusing to shut down his website Mormonstories.org &#124; Daily Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=February 10, 2015 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=(19 years ago) |url=http://voters.findthedata.com/l/78808477/John-Parkinson-Dehlin |title=John Parkinson Dehlin &#124; Utah Voter |publisher=Voters.findthedata.com |date= |accessdate=April 18, 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Boise, Idaho]], US\n| alma_mater         = [[Brigham Young University]] (BS)<br />[[Utah State University]] (MS, PhD)<ref name=\"johndehlin.com\">{{cite web|url=http://johndehlin.com/privatepractice/ |title=Private Practice \u2013 John Dehlin, Ph.D |publisher=Johndehlin.com |date= 2015-07-24|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| occupation         = [[New media]] [[journalist]] and [[Pundit|commentator]]<br />Scholar<br /> [[Moral entrepreneur]] <br />[[Faith crisis]] [[Coaching|coach]]<br />\n| spouse             = Margi Weber Dehlin<ref name=Tedxusu/>\n| children           = \n| website            = http://johndehlin.com/\n}}\n\n'''John Parkinson Dehlin'''<ref>{{cite web|author={{ authors[i].name }} |url=https://www.scribd.com/user/298878004/John-Parkinson-Dehlin |title=John Parkinson Dehlin (john1parkinson1dehli) 2 uploads |publisher=Scribd |date=September 28, 2015 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|'|l|\u026a|n}} is a podcast host and excommunicated member of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church). Dehlin founded the [[Mormon Stories Podcast]], as well as several other [[Mormon]]-themed [[podcast]]s, [[blog]]s, and web sites,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mormonstories.org |title=Mormon Stories Podcast  |publisher=openstoriesfoundation.org |date= |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> and was an influential early participant in the [[Mormon blogosphere]], and blogs at [[Patheos.com]]. He has advocated for the rights of [[Religious skepticism|skeptics]] in Mormonism, [[LGBT]] rights, equality for women, and other individual views outside mainstream Mormonism.<ref name=\"johndehlin.com\"/><ref name=Tedxusu>{{citation |contribution-url= http://www.ted.com/tedx/events/9015 |contribution= TEDxUSU: Survive |place= [[Utah State University]] |url= http://www.ted.com/tedx/events |title= TEDx Events  |publisher= [[TED.com]] |date= November 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Post by Joanna Brooks |url=http://www.religiondispatches.org/dispatches/joannabrooks/4859/landmark_survey_of_lgbtq_mormons_launched_/ |title=Landmark Survey of LGBTQ Mormons Launched |publisher=Religion Dispatches |date=July 13, 2011 |accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Youth and early career==\nBorn in [[Boise, Idaho]] and raised in [[Katy, Texas]],<ref name=MMprofile>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Author Profile: John Dehlin|work=Mormon Matters|url=http://mormonmatters.org/author/admin/|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828230534/http://mormonmatters.org/author/admin/|archive-date=August 28, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he attended [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) in [[Provo, Utah]].  He graduated [[summa cum laude]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[political science]] in 1993.<ref name=OCWCprofile>{{cite web|title=User Profile: John Dehlin |publisher=OpenCourseWare Consortium |url=http://ohana.mit.edu/ocwc/display/~jdehlin |accessdate=July 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908043216/http://ohana.mit.edu/ocwc/display/~jdehlin |archivedate=September 8, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Dehlin worked for five years in software and as a consultant for [[Bain & Company]], [[Arthur Andersen]], [[Citicorp]], Heidrick & Struggles, and the LDS Church. He then worked at [[Microsoft]] for seven years in programs for [[Software developer|developers]], [[marketing]], speech technologies, and [[Tech demo|product demos]].<ref name=OCWCprofile/> Dehlin's brother, [[Joel Dehlin]], also worked at Microsoft, and became the [[chief information officer]] of the LDS Church in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, Joel |title=About Joel |work=Joel Dehlin Weblog |url=http://www.ldscio.org/about-joel/ |accessdate=December 8, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517085205/http://www.ldscio.org/about-joel/ |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Dehlin moved to [[Logan, Utah]], to begin work under [[David A. Wiley]] at [[Utah State University]] (USU) on [[OpenCourseWare]]-related projects.<ref name=OCWCpost>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Meet and Greet|date=March 15, 2007|work=OpenCourseWare Consortium Forum|publisher=OpenCourseWare Consortium|url=http://www.ocwconsortium.org/ocwcforum/viewtopic.php?t=6&sid=a9d7085c396ee8d6167b01af7ae91ebf|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604003628/http://www.ocwconsortium.org/ocwcforum/viewtopic.php?t=6|archive-date=June 4, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  Dehlin would serve two years as USU's OpenCourseWare Consortium Coordinator and Director of Outreach for the Center for Open and Sustainable Learning, promoting OpenCourseWare to other universities,<ref name=OCWCprofile/> and a few years as director of the [[OpenCourseWare]] Consortium for the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]. In 2007, while at USU, Dehlin also completed a [[Master of Science]] degree in [[Instructional Technology]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=I did it|work=Mormon Stories|date=December 16, 2007|url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=376|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> In January 2007, [[MIT]] hired Dehlin as the Director of the [[OpenCourseWare]] Consortium.<ref name=OCWCpost/> In 2015 Dehlin received his doctorate in clinical and counseling psychology at USU.<ref name=\"USU University Libraries\">{{Cite journal | url=http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/etd/4251/ | title=USU University Libraries | journal=All Graduate Theses and Dissertations | accessdate=August 22, 2015| date=May 2015 | last1=Dehlin | first1=John }}</ref>\n\n==New media==\n===Sunstone===\nDuring Dehlin's early career developing [[massive open online course]]s (MOOCs) he had branched into Latter-day Saint themed [[new media]]. Dehlin approached the [[Sunstone Education Foundation]] and presented to its Board of Directors about the importance of participating in developing internet communities through blogging and podcasting, in order to address the then limited internet presence for constructive Mormon intellectual sources. The Board accepted his offer to initiate these programs<ref name=MStar>{{cite web|author=Goble, Clark|title=M* Interviews\u2026 John Dehlin|work=The Millennial Star|date=September 26, 2005|url=http://www.millennialstar.org/2005/09/26/m-interviews-john-dehlin/|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131021185604/http://www.millennialstar.org/m-interviews-john-dehlin/|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> and, in September 2005, Dehlin joined the Board of Directors and began a Sunstone podcast as well as ''SunstoneBlog''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wotherspoon, Dan |title=Bloggin and Podcasting Sunstone Style! |date=September 15, 2005 |work=SunstoneBlog |publisher=Sunstone Education Foundation |url=http://sunstoneblog.com/2005/09/15/blogging-and-podcasting-sunstone-style/ |accessdate=July 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905111435/http://sunstoneblog.com/2005/09/15/blogging-and-podcasting-sunstone-style/ |archivedate=September 5, 2008 }}</ref>  In July 2007, he also became executive director of the Sunstone Education Foundation, in which he was to focus on strategic initiatives to strengthen Sunstone's position as an open forum for Mormon issues.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunstone foundation hires executive director|date=July 28, 2007|work=[[Deseret News]]|url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,695195330,00.html|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>  In that role, he increased organizational focus on its longstanding motto, \"faith seeking understanding\", and worked to attract new and younger membership.<ref>{{cite news|author=Moore, Carrie A.|title=New direction for Sunstone?|work=[[Deseret Morning News]]|date=August 7, 2007|location=Salt Lake City|url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,695198451,00.html?pg=1|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>  Dehlin resigned from Sunstone in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=<comment>|work=The New Mormon History|publisher=Latter-day Commentary|date=June 8, 2008|url=http://latterdaycommentary.blogspot.com/2008/05/new-mormon-history-grant-palmer.html#c474708688441700241|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Mormon Stories'' ===\n{{main|Mormon Stories Podcast}}\nIn September 2005, after experiencing doubts in his faith and subsequently finding reasons to remain a member of the LDS Church, Dehlin created the Mormon Stories podcast as an open discussion of Mormon issues, intending to give listeners reasons to remain in the church.<ref name=MS1>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Mormon Stories Podcast # 001: Bad Baptisms? My Mission Experience in Guatemala|work=Mormon Stories|date=September 4, 2005|url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=4|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> Through interviews, Mormon Stories focused on varying Mormon experiences and perspectives. <!--To date, listenership at times exceeds 25,000 downloads per episode.--> Mormon Stories has been featured in many venues, including being broadcast on [[KVNU]] in [[Logan, Utah]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Grover, Tom|title=John Dehlin, Mormon Stories featured in today's Herald Journal|date=January 3, 2008|publisher=KVNU\u2019s For The People|url=http://kvnuforthepeople.com/?p=1258|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIntermittently conflicted about continuing ''Mormon Stories'', Dehlin stopped and restarted the project a few times.<ref name=WhatIsWas>{{cite web | title=What is/was Mormon Stories? | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=April 14, 2009 |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:2i027H1AlakJ:mormonstories.org/%3Fp%3D478+site:mormonstories.org+%22creative+commons%22&cd=2&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us&client=firefox-a}} {{dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Some Bonus Material, and a Break | date=December 25, 2007 | work=Mormon Stories | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=383 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref>  In January 2010 Dehlin resumed the blog and podcast, focusing on faith crises and mental illness. The podcast has featured many notable guests,<ref>{{cite web | title=Mormon Stories 2010 \u2014 A New Direction | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=January 15, 2010 | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=716 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref> beginning with interviews of [[Joanna Brooks]] and [[John C. Hamer]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Mormon Stories # 112 & 113: Joanna Brooks Parts 1 and 2 | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=January 20, 2010 | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=738 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Mormon Stories # 116: John Hamer Pt. 1 \u2014 The LDS Succession Crisis of 1844 and the Beginnings of the RLDS Church | work=Mormon Stories Podcast | date=January 24, 2010 | url=http://mormonstories.org/?p=792 | accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref> Two other regular hosts joined Dehlin in conducting interviews for the podcast: Dan Wotherspoon, former editor of ''[[Sunstone (magazine)|Sunstone]]'' magazine; and Natasha Helfer Parker, a licensed clinical marriage and family therapist.\n\n=== Other blogs ===\n\nIn June 2007, Dehlin started ''Mormon Matters'' as a blog and weekly podcast.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mormonmatters.org/mormon-matters-undergoing-re-design/ | title=About&#124;Mormon Matters | accessdate=May 22, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608115748/http://mormonmatters.org/mormon-matters-undergoing-re-design/ | archive-date=June 8, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>  The format was a discussion panel on events, culture, politics and spirituality within Mormonism.  Panelists were to represent different sides of each issue, although the show later struggled to retain regular conservative LDS panelists.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Desperately Seeking Conservative LDS Panelist(s)|work=Mormon Matters blog|date=July 14, 2007|url=http://mormonmatters.org/2007/07/14/desperately-seeking-lds-conservative-panelists/|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828221809/http://mormonmatters.org/2007/07/14/desperately-seeking-lds-conservative-panelists/|archive-date=August 28, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In early 2008, Dehlin converted ''Mormon Matters'' into a group blog and lessened emphasis on new podcast episodes,.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dehlin, John|title=Looking to turn Mormon Matters into a Group Blog|work=Mormon Matters blog|date=January 9, 2008|url=http://mormonmatters.org/2008/01/09/looking-to-turn-mormon-matters-into-a-group-blog/|accessdate=July 21, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726231246/http://mormonmatters.org/2008/01/09/looking-to-turn-mormon-matters-into-a-group-blog/|archive-date=July 26, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Dehlin resumed the ''Mormon Matters'' podcast on March 5, 2011 with Dan Wotherspoon as the host, and [[Joanna Brooks]] as a frequent co-host.\n\nDehlin is also the co-founder of the pro-LGBT ''Mormons for Marriage'' website.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.mormonsformarriage.com | title=Mormons for Marriage}}</ref> He  co-founded ''[[Stay LDS]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staylds.com |title=Stay LDS / Mormon &#124; New Ways to Stay Connected |publisher=Staylds.com |date= |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref> a community that was dedicated to helping unorthodox Mormons stay in the LDS Church.<ref>{{cite news | author=Dobner, Jennifer | title=Mormons in crisis find online refuge | work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]] | date=July 20, 2009 | url=http://www.sltrib.com/faith/ci_12871883 | accessdate=January 28, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604200157/http://www.sltrib.com/faith/ci_12871883 | archive-date=June 4, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDehlin briefly blogged at a non-partisan religion website [[Patheos.com]] in a current-issues/events dialogue format with [[Mormon studies]] scholar [[Patrick Q. Mason]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/4373196-155/lds-scholar-ex-mormon-team-up-on|title=LDS scholar, ex-Mormon team up on new blog to debate key topics facing the faith|first=Peggy Fletcher Stack The Salt Lake|last=Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==LDS Church membership==\nFrom 1988 to 1990, Dehlin served as an LDS Church [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary]] in Guatemala. According to Dehlin, his [[Mission (LDS Church)|mission]] began baptizing up to 700 converts per month using practices he believed to be deceptive. After reporting this to an  [[apostle (Latter Day Saints)|apostle]], [[Dallin H. Oaks]], Dehlin was transferred and finished his two-year missionary term in Tempe, Arizona. Dehlin remained an active, faithful member of the LDS Church for the next 20 years.<ref name=MS1/>\n\nIn the Spring of 2011, Dehlin stated he had become inactive in the LDS Church (i.e., not attending weekly services), citing an inability to believe some of the church's claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.newordermormon.org/viewtopic.php?t=20463 |title=New Order Mormon \u2022 View topic - Conversation on FB with a friend, because oh John Dehlin |publisher=Forum.newordermormon.org |date= |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postmormon.org/exp_e/index.php/discussions/viewthread/28352/ |title=Support for People as they Leave or Consider Leaving the Mormon or LDS Church &#124; The Community Forum &#124; Yes, John Dehlin has left the Church |publisher=PostMormon.org |date= |accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, Dehlin was investigated by his local church leaders regarding his online activity, culminating in a request by Dehlin for greater privacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mormonstories.org/did-you-ask-to-be-excommunicated/ |title=Did you ask to be excommunicated? |publisher=Mormon Stories |date= 2014-06-27|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2014, Dehlin had faced church disciplinary hearings without any resulting disciplinary action.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|last1=Walch|first1=Tad|title=Mormon critic John Dehlin says he'll face church disciplinary council|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865619676/Mormon-critic-John-Dehlin-says-hell-face-church-disciplinary-council.html?pg=all|accessdate=May 28, 2015|newspaper=Deseret News|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref> In January 2015, Dehlin's [[stake president]] initiated another disciplinary council,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goodstein|first1=Laurie|title=John Dehlin, Mormon Critic, Facing Excommunication|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/16/us/john-dehlin-mormon-critic-facing-excommunication.html|accessdate=January 15, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.sltrib.com/home/2089207-155/disciplinary-council-delayed-for-mormon-stories|newspaper = Salt Lake Tribune|title = Disciplinary council delayed for 'Mormon Stories' podcaster John Dehlin|first = Kristen|last = Moulton|date = January 22, 2015}}</ref> which determined Dehlin's online activity constituted apostasy.  He was [[Excommunication#The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|excommunicated]] for \"conduct contrary to the laws and order of the church.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name = walch>{{cite web|url = http://www.ksl.com/?sid=33422568&nid=148&title=john-dehlin-excommunicated-from-lds-church|publisher = KSL|title = John Dehlin excommunicated from LDS Church|first = Tad |last = Walch|date =February 10, 2015}}</ref> Dehlin appealed to the [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] on March 10, 2015, stating his actions had not met the church's definition of apostasy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/2275172-155/mormon-critic-john-dehlin-appeals-lds| newspaper=Salt Lake Tribune|title=Mormon critic John Dehlin appeals LDS excommunication| first = Peggy|last=Fletcher Stack|date = March 10, 2015|authorlink=Peggy Fletcher Stack}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/03/11/mormon-critic-john-dehlin-appeals-lds-excommunication/ |title=Mormon critic John Dehlin appeals LDS excommunication &#124; Religion News Service |publisher=Religionnews.com |date=March 11, 2015 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.newsweek.com/mormon-church-jesus-christ-latter-day-saints-james-hamula-648468 | title=Will we ever know why the Mormons booted out a top official for the first time in decades?| date=2017-08-09}}</ref> In July and August 2015, the First Presidency notified Dehlin via his stake president of the denial of his appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hjnews.com/allaccess/dehlin-upset-over-church-handling-of-excommunication-appeal/article_8fbf45da-5106-5a18-bf02-c02eebf70cbf.html|title=Dehlin upset over church handling of excommunication appeal|first=Kevin Opsahl staff|last=writer}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://johndehlin.com/ Official site]\n* [http://mormonstories.org/ ''Mormon Stories''], Dehlin's most well-known blog and podcast\n* [http://mormonstories.org/?page_id=102 Dehlin's list of episodes for ''Mormon Stories'', ''Sunstone'', and ''Mormon Matters'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140715092531/http://mormonmatters.org/2009/08/20/5-questions-after-5-years-%E2%80%93-from-a-longtime-%E2%80%98nacle-wannabe/ \"5 Questions After 5 Years \u2013 From A Longtime 'Nacle Wannabe,\"] by John Dehlin\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100119005050/http://ldspsychology.com/ Ldspsychology.com], one of Dehlin's blogs, started in 2009\n*{{Cite journal|title = The Odd Couple: Story and Community: John Dehlin's Mormon Stories project has a contradiction at its center. Whether it's a fatal error or a brilliant accident is yet to be seen|first = Rosalynde|last = Welch|date = June 28, 2012|publisher = [[Patheos]]|url = http://www.patheos.com/Mormon/Odd-Couple-Rosalynde-Welch-06-29-2012.html}}