entives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=RI20F&re=1&ee=1 Local Option - Property Tax Exemption for Renewable Energy Systems] (Property)\n|-\n|South Dakota || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=SD12F&re=1&ee=1 Large Commercial Wind Exemption and Alternative Taxes] (Property), [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=SD51F&re=1&ee=1 Renewable Energy System Exemption] (Property), [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=SD05F&re=1&ee=1 Small Commercial Wind Energy Property Tax Assessment] (Property)\n|-\n|Tennessee || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=TN03F&re=1&ee=1 Wind Energy Systems Exemption] (Property)\n|-\n|Texas || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=TX03F&re=1&ee=1 Renewable Energy Systems Property Tax Exemption] (Property)\n|-\n| Utah || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=UT03F&re=1&ee=0 Renewable Energy Systems Tax Credit] (Personal)\n|-\n|Vermont || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=VT02F&re=1&ee=1 Local Option - Property Tax Exemption] (Property)\n|-\n|West Virginia || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=WV01F&re=1&ee=1 Special Assessment for Wind Energy Systems] (Property)\n|-\n|Wisconsin || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=WI01F&re=1&ee=1 Solar and Wind Energy Equipment Exemption] (Property)\n|}\n\n==Renewable Portfolio Standards (RPS)==\nRenewable Portfolio Standards are written policy designed to require retail power suppliers to provide a certain minimum percentage of electricity, from a specific renewable power source, for a specified period of time.<ref name=\"Energy Bible\"/>  RPS programs are often used because of the energy, environmental, and economic benefits created by using renewable energy.  RPS programs create market demand for renewable energy supplies by aiming to stimulate the energy market to make clean energy economically competitive with conventional forms of electric power.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>  According to The Environmental Protection Agency in \"[http://www.epa.gov/chp/state-policy/renewable_fs.html Renewable Portfolio Standards: An Effective Policy to Support Clean Energy Supply]\", current states with RPS requirements mandate that 4% - 30%  of electricity be generated from renewable sources by a specified date, however, Renewable Portfolio Standards can have multiple goals.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>  Current RPS programs also include goals for local, regional, or global environmental benefits, local economic development, reducing the risks fossil fuel pricing, and advancing renewable energy technologies.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>\n\nThere are two types of Renewable Portfolio Standards: mandatory and voluntary.  As stated before, mandatory markets require the electricity service providers a minimum amount of renewable energy in their electricity supply while voluntary electricity markets allow the consumer to choose to surpass required policy and reduce the environmental impact of their electricity use further than required. Mandatory RPS programs are rarely applied to municipal utilities which are usually self regulated, but rather to investor-owned utilities and electric service providers.<ref name=\"epa.gov\">{{cite web|title=Renewable Portfolio Standards: An Effective Policy to Support Clean Energy Supply|url=http://www.epa.gov/chp/state-policy/renewable_fs.html|publisher=United States Environmental Protection Agency|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref>  Voluntary markets help create renewable energy capacity that exceeds what mandatory markets contribute nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Voluntary and Mandatory Markets|url=http://www.epa.gov/greenpower/gpmarket/markets.htm|publisher=Environmental Protection Agency|accessdate=2011-04-17}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the EPA, based on knowledge gained from states with successful Renewable Portfolio Standards, designing and implementing an effective RPS program relies heavily on: support of state government, facilitated discussions with important stakeholders focusing on an appropriate RPS design, clear goals and objectives, and designing a clear and easy-to-use accounting system for compliance.  It is also important to conduct a mid-term performance review.  This should be done to identify the causes for any delay in meeting the RPS targets, and to make program changes as needed to meet the original goals of the RPS.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>  As of 2009 33 states including Washington DC had enacted successful Renewable Portfolio Standards, and currently there are 37.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/> In 2003 RPS programs produced more than 2,300 megawatts (MW) of new renewable energy capacity.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/> In February 2009, the Union of Concerned Scientists project stated that RPS will account for 76,750 megawatts (MW) of new renewable power by 2025.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>\n\nBelow is a table of the current states with  Renewable Portfolio Standards. For more information on wind policy see also [http://www.dsireusa.org/ Database of State Incentives for Renewables & Efficiency].\n\n'''Table 2:''' State Renewable Portfolio Standards for renewable energy from the Database of State Incentives for Renewables and Efficiency (DSIRE) \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-!</big>'''State''' !! </big>'''Renewable Portfolio Standards'''\n|-\n|Arizona || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=AZ03R&re=1&ee=1 RPS: 15% by 2025]\n|-\n|California || [http://www.dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=CA25R&re=1&ee=1 RPS: 20% by 2010 and 33% by 2020]\n|-\n|Colorado || [https://web.archive.org/web/20120511065100/http://dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=CO24R&re=1&ee=1 RPS: Investor-owned utilities 30% by 2020, Electric cooperatives 10% by 2020, Municipal utilities serving more than 40,000 customers 10% by 2020]\n|-\n|Connecticut || [http: